# Actuary (Insurance Company)

## Overview
Actuaries in insurance companies apply mathematical models and statistical analysis to assess insurance risk, price products, establish reserves for future claims, and ensure adequate capital to meet regulatory obligations.

## Core Responsibilities
- Develop premium rates for insurance products based on expected claims costs, expenses, profit margins, and competitive market positioning using statistical models
- Calculate outstanding claims liabilities using actuarial methods and monitor claims development patterns to ensure adequate reserves for unpaid claims
- Design new insurance products with appropriate risk-based pricing, analyzing market opportunities and assessing profitability across customer segments
- Assess required capital under APRA prudential standards, model internal risk appetite, and optimize reinsurance structures to transfer risk efficiently
- Monitor actual versus expected claims experience, investigate cost trends, adjust pricing assumptions, and recommend corrective actions to maintain profitability
- Prepare actuarial reports for APRA regulatory compliance, value technical provisions under accounting standards, and provide professional advice to Board

## Key Skills Required

### Technical & Analytical
- Advanced mathematics and statistics including probability distributions, regression, GLMs, and actuarial methods
- Excel proficiency with complex formulas, macros, and data manipulation plus statistical programming in R/Python/SQL
- Understanding of insurance products, pricing methodologies, reserving techniques, loss modelling, and catastrophe risk
- Actuarial software knowledge including ResQ, Earnix, Igloo, and Radar for specialized pricing and reserving applications

### Professional & Interpersonal
- Clear communication of technical concepts to non-actuaries including executives, underwriters, and Board members
- Attention to detail and accuracy as small errors can have material financial impact on company reserves and profitability
- Time management balancing work deadlines, quarterly reporting cycles, and professional exam study commitments
- Professional judgment in selecting appropriate models, setting reasonable assumptions, and balancing precision with practicality

### Regulatory & Business
- Understanding of APRA prudential standards (GPS 310, 320, 340) and AASB 17 accounting standards for insurance liabilities
- Actuaries Institute Code of Conduct, professional standards, and Continuous Professional Development requirements
- Business acumen including company strategy, competitive dynamics, portfolio profitability drivers, and market positioning

## Work Mode

### Analytical Work (50-70%)
Excel modelling, statistical programming in R/Python, building and testing pricing algorithms, running reserving analyses, developing GLMs to predict claims frequency and severity, validating model outputs, and data quality checks

### Meetings & Collaboration (15-40%)
Daily team stand-ups, pricing committee presentations, reserve review sessions with senior actuaries, cross-functional meetings with underwriting/claims/finance teams, Board presentations (senior levels), and APRA engagement

### Study & Professional Development (10-15% early career, decreasing)
Actuaries Institute exam preparation (Parts I, II, III to Associate; Fellowship exams), reading research papers and industry publications, attending actuarial society events and seminars, completing CPD requirements

### Documentation & Reporting (5-15%)
Writing methodology notes and assumption documentation, preparing quarterly reporting packs, contributing to APRA filings, documenting model governance and validation, preparing Financial Condition Reports

### Team Leadership & Strategy (15-40% senior levels)
Managing analyst teams, delegating work, providing technical guidance, setting methodology standards, advising Board on risk appetite and capital strategy, representing company externally at conferences and with regulators

## Workplace Culture
Collaborative environment with dedicated actuarial teams working closely with underwriting, claims, and finance. Mix of technical analysis and stakeholder communication with strong professional development culture.

## Career Path
- Entry: Actuarial Graduate/Analyst (0-2 years, studying for professional exams)
- Progression: Senior Analyst (2-5 years, achieving AIAA Associate) → Actuary (5-8 years, progressing to FIAA Fellow, signing authority) → Senior/Chief Actuary (8-15 years, leading actuarial function, advising Board) → Potential moves to Chief Risk Officer, CFO, or CEO roles

